        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer261131167" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer392034759764167614">Art Atchinson Aimesworth is a jack of all trades. He is a creative inventor, brave enough for adventures, and excellent at fighting crime. So, when a mysterious box comes his way, he is determined to go where it leads him--to Santa Claus. One little problem. If Art doesn&apos;t take his little sister, Esther, with him, she will tattle and end the quest. Art concedes and soon the siblings are flying to the North Pole. To their surprise, everything isn&apos;t as cheery as they hoped and Art must use his wit</span>
  <span id="freeText392034759764167614" style="display:none">Art Atchinson Aimesworth is a jack of all trades. He is a creative inventor, brave enough for adventures, and excellent at fighting crime. So, when a mysterious box comes his way, he is determined to go where it leads him--to Santa Claus. One little problem. If Art doesn't take his little sister, Esther, with him, she will tattle and end the quest. Art concedes and soon the siblings are flying to the North Pole. To their surprise, everything isn't as cheery as they hoped and Art must use his wit to save the day.<br /><br />Joyce's story is somewhat random and wild, but children will certainly love the unpredictability of Art and Esther's adventure. I personally liked the ending, especially the two letters found at the end of the book. The illustrations are detailed and if you look closely, they seem to tell a story of their own.<br /><br /></span>
